Zelenskyy was inaugurated on 20 May 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ukraine's New President Vows To Dissolve Parliament As PM, Other Key Officials Resign |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/29951792.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520043757/https://www.rferl.org/a/29951792.html |archive-date=20 May 2019 |access-date=20 May 2019 |website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty}}</ref> Various foreign officials attended the ceremony in Ukraine's parliament ([[Verkhovna Rada]]), including [[Salome Zourabichvili]] ([[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]), [[Kersti Kaljulaid]] ([[Estonia]]), [[Raimonds Vējonis]] ([[Latvia]]), [[Dalia Grybauskaitė]] ([[Lithuania]]), [[János Áder]] ([[Hungary]]), [[Maroš Šefčovič]] ([[European Union]]), and [[Rick Perry]] (United States).<ref>{{cite web |title=Volodymyr Zelenskyy promised international partners that the world would be proud of Ukraine |url=https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/volodimir-zelenskij-poobicyav-mizhnarodnim-partneram-sho-svi-55501 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526070311/https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/volodimir-zelenskij-poobicyav-mizhnarodnim-partneram-sho-svi-55501 |archive-date=26 May 2019 |access-date=20 May 2019 |website=Official website of the President of Ukraine}}</ref> Zelenskyy is the first Jewish president; with [[Volodymyr Groysman]] as prime minister, Ukraine became the first country other than [[Israel]] to simultaneously have a Jewish head of state and head of government.<ref name="nyt1" /> In his inaugural address, Zelenskyy dissolved the [[8th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada|then Ukrainian parliament]] and called for [[Snap election|early parliamentary elections]] (which had originally been due to be held in October of that year).<ref>{{Cite news |date=20 May 2019 |title=New Ukraine President Zelensky calls snap election |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-48330955 |url-status=live |access-date=20 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520041907/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-48330955 |archive-date=20 May 2019}}</ref> One of Zelenskyy's coalition partners, the [[People's Front (Ukraine)|People's Front]], opposed the move and withdrew from the ruling coalition.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zelensky may dissolve parliament despite People's Front withdrawal from coalition – expert |url=https://www.unian.info/politics/10553196-zelensky-may-dissolve-parliament-despite-people-s-front-withdrawal-from-coalition-expert.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520094624/https://www.unian.info/politics/10553196-zelensky-may-dissolve-parliament-despite-people-s-front-withdrawal-from-coalition-expert.html |archive-date=20 May 2019 |access-date=20 May 2019 |website=www.unian.info}}</ref>

On 28 May, Zelenskyy restored the Ukrainian citizenship of [[Mikheil Saakashvili]].<ref>{{cite web |date=28 May 2019 |title=Georgia's Saakashvili has Ukrainian citizenship restored |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-48437792 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630121001/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-48437792 |archive-date=30 June 2019 |access-date=29 May 2019 |website=bbc.com}}</ref>

Zelenskyy's first major proposal to change the electoral system from a [[plurality voting]] system to [[proportional representation]] with [[Closed list|closed party lists]] was strongly rejected by the [[Ukrainian parliament]], due to the belief that closed lists would lead to more corruption in government.<ref>{{cite web |title=UAWire – Ukrainian parliament rejects Zelensky's proposal to change election system |url=http://www.uawire.org/ukrainian-parliament-rejects-zelensky-s-proposal-to-change-election-system |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609094219/http://www.uawire.org/ukrainian-parliament-rejects-zelensky-s-proposal-to-change-election-system |archive-date=9 June 2019 |access-date=9 June 2019 |website=www.uawire.org}}</ref>

In addition, on 6 June, lawmakers refused to include Zelenskyy's key initiative on reintroducing criminal liability for illegal enrichment in the parliament's agenda, and instead included a similar bill proposed by a group of deputies.<ref>{{cite web |trans-title=Rada refused to consider Zelensky's bill on liability for illegal enrichment |script-title=uk:Рада відмовилась розглядати законопроект Зеленського про відповідальність за незаконне збагачення |url=https://www.unian.ua/politics/10576860-rada-vidmovilas-rozglyadati-zakonoproekt-zelenskogo-pro-vidpovidalnist-za-nezakonne-zbagachennya.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609094220/https://www.unian.ua/politics/10576860-rada-vidmovilas-rozglyadati-zakonoproekt-zelenskogo-pro-vidpovidalnist-za-nezakonne-zbagachennya.html |archive-date=9 June 2019 |access-date=9 June 2019 |website=www.unian.ua |language=uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Рада включила в повестку дня депутатский законопроект об ответственности за незаконное обогащение, инициативу Зеленского рассматривать отказались |url=https://gordonua.com/news/politics/rada-vklyuchila-v-povestku-dnya-deputatskiy-zakonoproekt-ob-otvetstvennosti-za-nezakonnoe-obogashchenie-iniciativu-zelenskogo-rassmatrivat-otkazalis-1019644.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609094222/https://gordonua.com/news/politics/rada-vklyuchila-v-povestku-dnya-deputatskiy-zakonoproekt-ob-otvetstvennosti-za-nezakonnoe-obogashchenie-iniciativu-zelenskogo-rassmatrivat-otkazalis-1019644.html |archive-date=9 June 2019 |access-date=9 June 2019 |website=gordonua.com}}{{better source needed|date=October 2019}}</ref> In June 2019 it was announced that the president's third major initiative, which seeks to remove immunity from lawmakers, diplomats and judges, would be submitted after the July [[2019 Ukrainian parliamentary election]].<ref>{{cite web |trans-title=President introduces bill on removing torture from deputies, diplomats and judges to new Rada - Stefanchuk |script-title=uk:Президент внесе у нову Раду законопроект про зняття недоторканності з депутатів, дипломатів та суддів – Стефанчук |url=https://www.unian.ua/politics/10577190-prezident-vnese-u-novu-radu-zakonoproekt-pro-znyattya-nedotorkannosti-z-deputativ-diplomativ-ta-suddiv-stefanchuk.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609094216/https://www.unian.ua/politics/10577190-prezident-vnese-u-novu-radu-zakonoproekt-pro-znyattya-nedotorkannosti-z-deputativ-diplomativ-ta-suddiv-stefanchuk.html |archive-date=9 June 2019 |access-date=9 June 2019 |website=www.unian.ua |language=uk}}</ref> This initiative was completed on 3 September, when the new parliament passed a bill stripping lawmakers of legal immunity, delivering Zelenskyy a legislative victory by fulfilling one of his key campaign promises.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Zinets |first1=Natalia |last2=Williams |first2=Matthias |date=3 September 2019 |title=Quick win for Zelenskiy as Ukraine parliament strips lawmakers' immunity |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-parliament-immunity-idUSKCN1VO0YU |access-date=14 March 2022 |archive-date=13 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220313192356/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-parliament-immunity-idUSKCN1VO0YU |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 8 July, Zelenskyy ordered the cancellation of the annual [[Kyiv Independence Day Parade]] on [[Maidan Nezalezhnosti]], citing costs. Despite this, Zelenskyy highlighted that [[Independence Day of Ukraine#2019|the day]] would "honor heroes" on Independence Day, however the "format will be new".<ref>{{cite web |title=Zelensky cancels Independence Day parade on August 24 citing costs |url=https://tass.com/world/1067803 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709172856/https://tass.com/world/1067803 |archive-date=9 July 2019 |access-date=9 July 2019 |website=TASS}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=9 July 2019 |title=Zelensky cancels Independence Day military parade, gives money to soldiers &#124; KyivPost – Ukraine's Global Voice |url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/zelenskiy-cancels-independence-day-military-parade-gives-money-to-soldiers.html |website=KyivPost |access-date=11 July 2019 |archive-date=9 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709185209/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/zelenskiy-cancels-independence-day-military-parade-gives-money-to-soldiers.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=No Independence Day parade to be held this year, Zelensky says |url=https://www.unian.info/society/10612035-no-independence-day-parade-to-be-held-this-year-zelensky-says.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717175254/https://www.unian.info/society/10612035-no-independence-day-parade-to-be-held-this-year-zelensky-says.html |archive-date=17 July 2019 |access-date=28 July 2019 |website=www.unian.info}}</ref> He also proposed to spend the money that would have been used to finance the parade on veterans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bonuses instead of parade: Ukraine's leader takes surprising decision |url=https://belsat.eu/en/news/bonuses-instead-of-parade-ukraine-s-leader-takes-surprising-decision/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711194934/https://belsat.eu/en/news/bonuses-instead-of-parade-ukraine-s-leader-takes-surprising-decision/ |archive-date=11 July 2019 |access-date=11 July 2019 |website=belsat.eu}}</ref>

In 2020, Zelenskyy's party proposed reforms to Ukraine's media laws with the intent to increase competition and loosen the dominance of [[Ukrainian oligarchs]] on television and radio broadcasters. Critics said it risked increasing [[Freedom of the press in Ukraine|media censorship in Ukraine]]<ref>{{cite web |date=6 February 2020 |title=Voice of America: Journalists see censorship in Ukraine's proposed media laws |url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/voice-of-america-journalists-see-censorship-in-ukraines-proposed-media-laws.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210317004525/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/voice-of-america-journalists-see-censorship-in-ukraines-proposed-media-laws.html |archive-date=17 March 2021 |access-date=28 December 2020 |website=Kyiv Post}}</ref> because its clause of criminal responsibility for the distribution of disinformation could be abused.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leonova |first1=Nataliya |last2=Lihostova |first2=Oksana |last3=Deynychenko |first3=Ruslan |date=5 February 2020 |title=Journalists See Specter of Censorship in Ukraine's Proposed Media Law |url=https://www.voanews.com/press-freedom/journalists-see-specter-censorship-ukraines-proposed-media-laws |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201205151528/https://www.voanews.com/press-freedom/journalists-see-specter-censorship-ukraines-proposed-media-laws |archive-date=5 December 2020 |access-date=28 December 2020 |website=VoA News}}</ref>

In January 2020, Zelenskyy took a trip to [[Oman]] that was not published on his official schedule, appearing to combine a personal holiday with government business. His office said Zelenskyy paid for the entire trip himself. Nevertheless he was criticised for a lack of transparency and critics pointed out he had once criticized his predecessor Poroshenko for taking an undisclosed vacation in the [[Maldives]].<ref name="pravdaua200105">{{cite news |url=https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/5/7236619/ |url-status=live |trans-title=Zelensky without extra announcement jetted off in Oman "for a meeting at the highest level |title=Зеленський без зайвих анонсів гайнув в Оман "на зустрічі на найвищому рівні" |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221200824/https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/5/7236619/|archive-date=21 February 2020 |work=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]] |date=5 January 2020 }}</ref><ref name="radiolib200106">{{cite news |first=Yevhen |last=Solonyna |url-status=live |url=https://www.radiosvoboda.org/a/30363260.html |trans-title=Zelensky in Oman. Experts tell about crisis in communications of the President |title=Зеленський в Омані. Експерти говорять про кризу комунікації президента |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221200823/https://www.radiosvoboda.org/a/30363260.html |archive-date=21 February 2020 |work=[[Radio Liberty]] |date=6 January 2020 }}</ref>

In January 2021, parliament passed a bill updating and reforming Ukraine's [[referendum]] laws,<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Shushkovska |first=Alisa |date=18 February 2021 |title=Ukraine adopts new and improved referendum law |url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/ukrainealert/ukraine-adopts-new-and-improved-referendum-law/ |access-date=2 March 2022 |website=[[Atlantic Council]] |language=en-US |archive-date=6 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210706060611/https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/ukrainealert/ukraine-adopts-new-and-improved-referendum-law/ |url-status=live }}</ref> which Ukraine's [[Constitutional Court of Ukraine|Constitutional Court]] had declared unconstitutional in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 April 2018 |title=Ukraine's referendum law passed during Yanukovych's presidency designated as unconstitutional |url=https://www.unian.info/politics/10097429-ukraine-s-referendum-law-passed-during-yanukovych-s-presidency-designated-as-unconstitutional.html |access-date=2 March 2022 |website=[[Unian]] |language=en |archive-date=2 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210302014940/https://www.unian.info/politics/10097429-ukraine-s-referendum-law-passed-during-yanukovych-s-presidency-designated-as-unconstitutional.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Fixing the referendum law had been one of Zelenskyy's campaign promises.<ref name=":4" />

In June 2021, Zelenskyy submitted to the [[Verkhovna Rada]] a bill creating a public registry of Ukraine's oligarchs, banning them from participating in privatizations of [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned companies]], and forbidding them from contributing financially to politicians. Opposition party leaders supported Zelenskyy's goal of reducing oligarchs' influence on politics in Ukraine but were critical of his approach, saying the public register would be both dangerous, as it concentrated power in the president; and ineffective, since oligarchs were merely a "symbol" of more deeply-rooted corruption.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Filtenborg |first1=Emil |last2=Weichert |first2=Stefan |date=22 June 2021 |title=Zelenskyy speeds up corruption crackdown, one oligarch at a time |url=https://www.euronews.com/my-europe/2021/06/22/ukraine-s-volodymyr-zelenskyy-speeds-up-corruption-crackdown-one-oligarch-at-a-time |access-date=6 March 2022 |website=Euronews |language=en |archive-date=9 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220309091422/https://www.euronews.com/my-europe/2021/06/22/ukraine-s-volodymyr-zelenskyy-speeds-up-corruption-crackdown-one-oligarch-at-a-time |url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was passed into law in September 2021.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Polityuk |first1=Pavel |last2=Zinets |first2=Natalia |date=23 September 2021 |title=Ukrainian lawmakers pass law on oligarchs after assassination attempt |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/ukrainian-parliament-passes-law-oligarchs-final-reading-2021-09-23/ |access-date=6 March 2022 |archive-date=5 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220305211546/https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/ukrainian-parliament-passes-law-oligarchs-final-reading-2021-09-23/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
Critics of Zelenskyy's administration have claimed that, in taking power away from the Ukrainian oligarchs, he has sought to centralize authority and strengthen his personal position.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Hall |first1=Ben |last2=Olearchyk |first2=Roman |last3=Seddon |first3=Max |date=21 October 2019 |title=Ukraine: why Volodymyr Zelensky is pursuing a disruptive agenda |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a99bceb2-ef59-11e9-bfa4-b25f11f42901 |url-status=live |access-date=20 February 2022 | issn = 0307-1766 | oclc = 801838674 | url-access = subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220220151416/https://www.ft.com/content/a99bceb2-ef59-11e9-bfa4-b25f11f42901 |archive-date=20 February 2022}}</ref>

=== Cabinets and administration ===
Zelenskyy appointed [[Andriy Bohdan]] as head of the [[Presidential Administration of Ukraine]]. Prior to this, Bohdan had been the lawyer of [[Ukrainian oligarchs|Ukrainian oligarch]] [[Ihor Kolomoyskyi]].<ref name="auto2">{{cite web |title=Нові кадри в Адміністрації. Кого Зеленський привів на Банкову |url=https://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2019/05/22/7215729/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521233012/https://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2019/05/22/7215729/ |archive-date=21 May 2019 |access-date=21 May 2019 |website=Українська правда}}</ref> Under the rules of [[Lustration in Ukraine]], introduced in 2014 following [[Euromaidan]], Bohdan is not entitled to hold any state office until 2024 (because of his government post during the [[Second Azarov Government]]).<ref>{{cite web |trans-title=New Personnel in the Administration. Who did Zelenskyy bring to Bankova |script-title=uk:Нові кадри в Адміністрації. Кого Зеленський привів на Банкову |url=https://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2019/05/22/7215729/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521233012/https://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2019/05/22/7215729/ |archive-date=21 May 2019 |access-date=23 May 2019 |website=Українська правда |language=uk}}</ref> Bohdan, however, contended that because heading the presidential administration is not considered civil service work, lustration did not apply to him.<ref>{{cite web |last=Карцев |first=Дмитрий |date=22 May 2019 |title=Владимир Зеленский руководит Украиной три дня. Вот что он сделал (и не сделал) |url=https://meduza.io/slides/vladimir-zelenskiy-rukovodit-ukrainoy-tri-dnya-vot-chto-on-sdelal-i-ne-sdelal |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524001559/https://meduza.io/slides/vladimir-zelenskiy-rukovodit-ukrainoy-tri-dnya-vot-chto-on-sdelal-i-ne-sdelal |archive-date=24 May 2019 |access-date=5 June 2019 |website=meduza.io}}</ref> A number of the members of the Presidential Administration Zelenskyy appointed were former colleagues from his former production company, [[Kvartal 95 Studio|Kvartal 95]],<ref name="auto2" /> including [[Ivan Bakanov]], who became deputy head of the [[Security Service of Ukraine|Ukrainian Secret Service]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Zelensky's childhood friend appointed SBU's first deputy chief (Document) |url=https://www.unian.info/politics/10558788-zelensky-s-childhood-friend-appointed-sbu-s-first-deputy-chief-document.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031023410/https://www.unian.info/politics/10558788-zelensky-s-childhood-friend-appointed-sbu-s-first-deputy-chief-document.html |archive-date=31 October 2019 |access-date=9 December 2019 |website=www.unian.info}}</ref> Former deputy foreign minister [[Olena Zerkal]] declined an appointment as deputy head of the presidential administration, but did agree to serve as the Ukrainian representative of the international courts concerning Russia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Зеркаль відмовилась від посади заступника глави АП – джерела |url=https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2019/05/22/7215732/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522080816/https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2019/05/22/7215732/ |archive-date=22 May 2019 |access-date=21 May 2019 |website=Українська правда}}</ref> Zelenskyy's requests to replace the foreign minister, [[defence minister]], chief prosecutor and head of Ukraine's security service were rejected by parliament.<ref>{{cite web |title=Рада отказала Зеленскому в увольнении двух министров и главы СБУ. Ни один из его законопроектов не рассмотрен |url=https://meduza.io/news/2019/06/06/rada-otkazala-zelenskomu-v-uvolnenii-dvuh-ministrov-i-glavy-sbu-ni-odin-iz-ego-zakonoproektov-ne-rassmotren |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609094220/https://meduza.io/news/2019/06/06/rada-otkazala-zelenskomu-v-uvolnenii-dvuh-ministrov-i-glavy-sbu-ni-odin-iz-ego-zakonoproektov-ne-rassmotren |archive-date=9 June 2019 |access-date=9 June 2019 |website=meduza.io |language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Даша |first=Зубкова |date=2 July 2019 |title=Zelenskyy Again Asking Rada To Dismiss Lutsenko And Klimkin, Appoint Prystaiko As Foreign Affairs Minister |url=https://press.ukranews.com/ |access-date=2 March 2022 |website=Ukranews.com |language=en |archive-date=3 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220303152823/https://press.ukranews.com/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Zelenskyy also dismissed and replaced 20 of the governors of Ukraine's 24 [[Oblasts of Ukraine|oblasts]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sorokin |first=Oleksiy |date=6 July 2019 |title=Zelensky appoints his first governors — in Lviv, Donetsk, Zakarpattia oblasts |url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/zelensky-appoints-his-first-governors-in-lviv-donetsk-oblasts.html |access-date=2 March 2022 |website=[[KyivPost]] |archive-date=2 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220202121133/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/zelensky-appoints-his-first-governors-in-lviv-donetsk-oblasts.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Honcharuk government ====
{{Main|Honcharuk Government}}
In the 21 July 2019 parliamentary election, Zelenskyy's political party, [[Servant of the People (political party)|Servant of the People]], won the first single-party majority in modern Ukrainian history in parliament, with 43 per cent of the party-list vote. His party gained 254 of the 424 seats.<ref>{{Cite news |date=25 July 2019 |title=Volodymyr Zelensky clears the old elite out of parliament |newspaper=The Economist |url=https://www.economist.com/europe/2019/07/25/volodymyr-zelensky-clears-the-old-elite-out-of-parliament |url-status=live |access-date=1 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806130025/https://www.economist.com/europe/2019/07/25/volodymyr-zelensky-clears-the-old-elite-out-of-parliament |archive-date=6 August 2019 |issn=0013-0613}}</ref>

Following the elections, Zelenskyy nominated [[Oleksiy Honcharuk]] as prime minister, who was quickly confirmed by parliament. Parliament also confirmed [[Andrii Zahorodniuk]] as defence minister, [[Vadym Prystaiko]] as foreign minister and [[Ivan Bakanov]] as head of the [[Security Service of Ukraine|SBU]].<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Talant |first1=Bermet |last2=Sorokin |first2=Oleksiy |date=29 August 2019 |title=Oleksiy Honcharuk named prime minister, Cabinet approved |url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/oleksiy-honcharuk-named-ukraines-new-prime-minister.html |access-date=1 March 2022 |website=KyivPost |archive-date=4 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220304222642/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/oleksiy-honcharuk-named-ukraines-new-prime-minister.html |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Arsen Avakov]], a controversial figure due to longstanding corruption allegations,<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 July 2021 |title=Ukrainian Parliament Accepts Resignation Of Influential Interior Minister |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-avakov-resignation-accepted/31359737.html |access-date=1 March 2022 |website=[[RadioFreeEurope]] |language=en |archive-date=27 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210827001500/https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-avakov-resignation-accepted/31359737.html |url-status=live }}</ref> was kept on as [[interior minister]], with Honcharuk arguing that the relatively inexperienced government needed experienced administrators and that Avakov had been "'drawn red lines' that cannot be crossed."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2019/08/30/7224875/ |trans-title=The new prime minister explained how Avakov was left – the "red lines" |title=Новий прем'єр пояснив, як лишили Авакова: "червоні лінії" |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331042412/https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2019/08/30/7224875/ |archive-date=31 March 2020 |work=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]] |date=30 August 2019 }}</ref>

Zelenskyy dismissed Bohdan as head of his presidential administration on 11 February 2020 and appointed [[Andriy Yermak]] as his successor the same day.<ref name="640533YermakZelensky">{{cite news |url=https://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/640533.html |title=Zelensky dismisses head of president's office Bohdan, appoints Yermak instead |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212142103/https://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/640533.html |archive-date=12 February 2020 |work=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=11 February 2020 }}</ref>

==== Shmyhal government ====
{{See also|Land reforms by country#Ukraine}}
On 6 March 2020, the Honcharuk government gave way to the [[Shmyhal Government|government]] of [[Denys Shmyhal]]. At the time, there was disquiet in the press over the hasty departure of Honcharuk.<ref name="btkp">{{Cite news |last=Talant |first=Bermet |date=6 March 2020 |title=Hasty government reshuffle sows disquiet at home, abroad |publisher=Kyiv Post |url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/hasty-government-reshuffle-sows-disquiet-at-home-abroad.html |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-date=9 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220309190737/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/hasty-government-reshuffle-sows-disquiet-at-home-abroad.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In his 4 March address to the Rada,<ref name="pukz">{{Cite news |last=ZELENSKYY |first=VOLODYMYR |date=4 March 2020 |title=Speech by President of Ukraine Volodymyr Zelenskyy at an extraordinary session of the Verkhovna Rada |publisher=PRESIDENT OF UKRAINE Official website |url=https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/vistup-prezidenta-ukrayini-volodimira-zelenskogo-na-pozacher-60017 |url-status=live |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200705151203/https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/vistup-prezidenta-ukrayini-volodimira-zelenskogo-na-pozacher-60017 |archive-date=5 July 2020}}</ref> Zelenskyy recommitted to reforms domestic and financial, and remarked that he "cannot always become a psychologist for people, a crisis manager for someone, a collector who requires honestly earned money, and a nanny of the ministry in charge."{{citation needed|date=August 2021}} By September 2020, Zelenskyy's approval ratings had fallen to less than 32 per cent.<ref>{{Cite news |date=21 September 2020 |title=Zelensky's approval rating slides to 31% – poll |work=[[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency]] |url=https://www.unian.info/politics/poll-zelensky-s-approval-rating-slides-to-31-11153930.html |url-status=live |access-date=15 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210415163338/https://www.unian.info/politics/poll-zelensky-s-approval-rating-slides-to-31-11153930.html |archive-date=15 April 2021}}</ref>
[[File:Робочий візит Президента України до Турецької Республіки 05.jpg|thumb|Zelenskyy and Turkish president [[Recep Tayyip Erdoğan]] on 16 October 2020]]
On 24 March 2021, Zelenskyy signed the Decree 117/2021 approving the "strategy for de-occupation and reintegration of the temporarily occupied territory of the [[Autonomous Republic of Crimea]] and the city of [[Sevastopol]]."<ref>{{Cite news |date=24 March 2021 |title=Zelensky enacts strategy for de-occupation and reintegration of Crimea |work=[[Ukrinform]] |url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-polytics/3214479-zelensky-enacts-strategy-for-deoccupation-and-reintegration-of-crimea.html |url-status=live |access-date=15 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211212130511/https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-polytics/3214479-zelensky-enacts-strategy-for-deoccupation-and-reintegration-of-crimea.html |archive-date=12 December 2021}}</ref>

=== Attempts to end the Donbas conflict ===
One of Zelenskyy's central campaign promises had been to end the [[Russo-Ukrainian War]] and resolve the Russia-sponsored separatist movement there.<ref name=":3">{{cite web |date=2 October 2019 |title=Ukraine conflict: Anger as Zelensky agrees vote deal in east |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-49903996 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112023118/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-49903996 |archive-date=12 November 2020 |access-date=28 December 2020 |website=BBC News}}</ref> On 3 June, Zelenskyy appointed former president [[Leonid Kuchma]] as Ukraine's representative in the [[Trilateral Contact Group on Ukraine|Tripartite Contact Group]] for a settlement in the conflict.<ref>{{cite web |title=Леонид Кучма возглавил украинскую делегацию в Трехсторонней контактной группе |trans-title=Leonid Kuchma heads the Ukrainian delegation in the Trilateral Contact Group |url=https://www.president.gov.ua/ru/news/leonid-kuchma-ocholiv-ukrayinsku-delegaciyu-tristoronnoyi-ko-55717 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604094452/https://www.president.gov.ua/ru/news/leonid-kuchma-ocholiv-ukrayinsku-delegaciyu-tristoronnoyi-ko-55717 |archive-date=4 June 2019 |access-date=8 June 2019 |website=Официальное интернет-представительство Президента Украины}}</ref> On 11 July 2019, Zelenskyy held his first telephone conversation with Russian president [[Vladimir Putin]], during which he urged Putin to enter into talks mediated by European countries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Telephone conversation with President of Ukraine Vladimir Zelensky |url=http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/60984 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712032252/http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/60984 |archive-date=12 July 2019 |access-date=12 July 2019 |website=President of Russia}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news |last=Foy |first=Henry |date=11 July 2019 |title=Putin and Zelensky hold first discussion with talks on conflict, prisoner swap |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/2c4b7cee-a3f7-11e9-974c-ad1c6ab5efd1 |url-status=live |access-date=12 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712032449/https://www.ft.com/content/2c4b7cee-a3f7-11e9-974c-ad1c6ab5efd1 |archive-date=12 July 2019}}</ref> The two leaders also discussed the exchange of prisoners held by both sides.<ref name=":1" /> In October 2019, Zelenskyy announced a preliminary deal struck with the separatists, under which the Ukrainian government would respect elections held in the region in exchange for Russia withdrawing its [[Little green men (Russo-Ukrainian War)|unmarked troops]].<ref name=":3" /> The deal was met with heavy criticism and [[No to capitulation!|protests]] by both politicians and the Ukrainian public. Detractors noted that elections held in Donbas were unlikely to be free and fair, that the separatists had long driven out most pro-Ukrainian residents out of the region to ensure a pro-Russia majority, and that it would be impossible to ensure Russia kept its end of the agreement.<ref name=":3" /> Zelenskyy defended his negotiations, saying the elections would not be held before a Russian withdrawal.<ref>{{cite web |date=6 October 2019 |title=Thousands protest Ukraine leader's peace plan |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191006-thousands-protest-ukraine-leader-s-peace-plan-2 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210115072102/https://www.france24.com/en/20191006-thousands-protest-ukraine-leader-s-peace-plan-2 |archive-date=15 January 2021 |access-date=8 March 2021 |website=France 24}}</ref> The agreement failed to ease the conflict, as the separatists continued their attacks and Russia continued providing them with weapons and ammunition.<ref name=":7">{{Cite web |last=Midttun |first=Hans Petter |date=25 December 2019 |title=The basis for a peaceful resolution of the war in eastern Ukraine – trends at the end of 2019 |url=https://euromaidanpress.com/2019/12/25/peaceful-resolution-of-the-war-in-eastern-ukraine-donbass-trends-at-the-end-of-2019/ |access-date=9 March 2022 |website=[[Euromaidan Press]] |archive-date=2 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220302163652/https://euromaidanpress.com/2019/12/25/peaceful-resolution-of-the-war-in-eastern-ukraine-donbass-trends-at-the-end-of-2019/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Several Ukrainian nationalist militias and former militias also refused to accept the agreement, including the far-right [[Azov Battalion|Azov]] fighters in the [[Luhansk Oblast|Luhansk region]] of Donbas. Zelenskyy met personally with some of these groups and tried to convince them to surrender their unregistered weapons and accept the peace accord. [[Andriy Biletsky]], the leader of the far-right [[National Corps]] and first commander of Azov, accused Zelenskyy of being disrespectful to army veterans and of acting on behalf of [[the Kremlin]] by leaving Ukrainians vulnerable to Russian aggression.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Krivosheev |first1=Kirill |title=Владимир Зеленский ушел без оружия |trans-title=Volodymyr Zelenskyy walks away unarmed |url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4140693 |access-date=9 March 2022 |work=[[Kommersant]] |date=27 October 2019 |language=ru |archive-date=23 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220223175950/https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4140693 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Far-right groups protest Ukrainian president's peace plan |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2019-10-14/ukraine-protest-zelensky-peace-plan |access-date=9 March 2022 |work=Los Angeles Times |agency=Associated Press |date=14 October 2019 |archive-date=9 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220309001840/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2019-10-14/ukraine-protest-zelensky-peace-plan |url-status=live }}</ref> Ultimately, the peace deal failed to reduce the violence, much less end the war.<ref name=":7" />

In December 2019, Russia and Ukraine agreed to resume talks mediated by France and Germany under the so-called [[Normandy Format]], which had been abandoned in 2016; it was Zelenskyy's first face-to-face meeting with Vladimir Putin.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wintour |first=Patrick |date=26 January 2022 |title=Ukraine tensions: what is the Normandy format and has it achieved anything? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/jan/26/ukraine-russia-tensions-what-is-the-normandy-format-and-has-it-achieved-anything |access-date=9 March 2022 |website=The Guardian |language=en |archive-date=3 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220303041837/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/jan/26/ukraine-russia-tensions-what-is-the-normandy-format-and-has-it-achieved-anything |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2020, Zelenskyy announced a formal [[ceasefire]] with the separatists — the more than twentieth such attempt since the war began in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cookman |first=Liz |title=Ukraine-Russia crisis: Ceasefire violations rise at contact line |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/2/1/ukraine-russia-crisis-ceasefire-violations-rise-at-contact-line |access-date=9 March 2022 |website=[[Aljazeera]] |language=en |archive-date=2 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220302010042/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/2/1/ukraine-russia-crisis-ceasefire-violations-rise-at-contact-line |url-status=live }}</ref> Although the ceasefire was frequently violated over the next few years and overall violence remained high, ceasefire violations in 2020 did decrease by over 50 per cent compared to the previous year.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ponomarenko |first=Illia |date=15 February 2021 |title=OSCE in Donbas reports 55% less ceasefire violations in 2020 |url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/osce-in-donbas-reports-55-less-ceasefire-violations-in-2020.html |access-date=9 March 2022 |website=KyivPost |archive-date=28 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210228205442/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/osce-in-donbas-reports-55-less-ceasefire-violations-in-2020.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== UIA Flight 752 ===
{{See also|Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752}}
On 8 January 2020, the Presidential Office announced that Volodymyr Zelenskyy was cutting his trip to Oman short owing to the [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]] plane crash in nearby [[Iran]] the same day.<ref>{{cite news | author = <!--not stated--> | date = 8 January 2020 | script-title = uk:Через катастрофу в Ірані Зеленський перервав поїздку до Оману | trans-title = Due to the catastrophe in Iran, Zelensky interrupted his trip to Oman | url = https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/8/7236780/ | url-status = live | script-work = uk:Українська правда | trans-work = [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] | language = uk | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200221211520/https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/8/7236780/ | archive-date = 21 February 2020 | access-date = 10 March 2022 }}</ref> The same day, internet news site Obozrevatel.com released information that on 7 January 2020, Ukrainian politician of the [[Opposition Platform — For Life]] [[Viktor Medvedchuk]] – who has exclusive relations with the current [[president of Russia]] – may have arrived in Oman.<ref name="Grigorenko_2020">{{cite news | last1 = Grigorenko | first1 = Timur | date = 8 January 2020 | script-title = ru:"Вылетаю!" Зеленский срочно покинул Оман из-за крушения самолета | trans-title = "I'm flying out!" Zelensky urgently left Oman due to plane crash | url = https://www.obozrevatel.com/crime/vyiletayu-zelenskij-srochno-pokinul-oman-iz-za-krusheniya-samoleta.htm | url-status = live | work = [[Obozrevatel]] | language = ru | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200221220442/https://www.obozrevatel.com/crime/vyiletayu-zelenskij-srochno-pokinul-oman-iz-za-krusheniya-samoleta.htm | archive-date = 21 February 2020 | access-date = 10 March 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = <!--not stated--> | date = 9 January 2020 | script-title = uk:Зеленський прилетів з Оману майже через добу після авіакатастрофи – "Схеми" | trans-title = Zelensky arrived from Oman almost a day after the plane crash - "Skhemy" | url = https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/9/7236873/ | url-status = live | script-work = uk:Українська правда | trans-work = [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] | language = uk | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200222015859/https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/9/7236873/ | archive-date = 22 February 2020 | access-date = 10 March 2022 }}</ref> Soon, rumors began that Zelenskyy may have had some additional meetings beside the ones that were announced.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://glavcom.ua/country/politics/v-omani-zelenskij-mig-zustrichatisja-iz-surkovim-zmi-652122.html |trans-title=In Oman Zelensky may have met with Surkov, mass media |title=В Омані Зеленський міг зустрічатися із Сурковим, – ЗМІ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222014547/https://glavcom.ua/country/politics/v-omani-zelenskij-mig-zustrichatisja-iz-surkovim-zmi-652122.html |archive-date=22 February 2020 |work=Glavcom.ua |date=12 January 2020 }}</ref> On 14 January 2020, [[Andriy Yermak]] dismissed the rumors as speculations and baseless conspiracy theories,<ref>{{cite news | author = <!--not stated--> | date = 14 January 2020 | script-title = uk:Зеленський і літак Медведчука в Омані: у президента прокоментували збіг | trans-title = Zelensky and Medvedchuk's plane in Oman: the president commented on the coincidence | url = https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/14/7237358/ | url-status = live | script-work = uk:Українська правда | trans-work = [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] | language = uk | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200222014549/https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/14/7237358/ | archive-date = 22 February 2020 | access-date = 10 March 2022 }}</ref> while Medvedchuk stated that the plane was used by his older daughter's family to fly from Oman to Moscow.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/14/7237338/ |url-status=live |trans-title=Medvedchuk told who flew in his plane from Oman, while there was Zelensky |title=Медведчук розповів, хто летів у його літаку з Оману, поки там був Зеленський |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222014547/https://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2020/01/14/7237338/ |archive-date=22 February 2020 |work=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]] |date=14 January 2020 }}</ref> Later, Yermak contacted the on-line newspaper [[Ukrayinska Pravda|Ukrainian Truth]] and gave more details about the visit to Oman and the plane crash in Iran.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Romaniuk | first1 = Roman | date = 14 January 2020 | script-title = uk:Андрій Єрмак: Зеленський повернувся з Оману настільки швидко, наскільки це було можливо | trans-title = Andriy Yermak: Zelensky returned from Oman as soon as possible | url = https://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2020/01/14/7237349/ | url-status = live | script-work = uk:Українська правда | trans-work = [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] | language = uk | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200213045010/https://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2020/01/14/7237349/ | archive-date = 13 February 2020 | access-date = 10 March 2022 }}</ref>

On 17 January 2020, the presidential appointee Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Vadym Prystaiko]] was unable to give answers during the "times of questions to the government" in parliament when the people's deputies of Ukraine asked him about the visit's official agenda, the invitation from Oman, officials of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs who were preparing the visit, as well as how the president actually crossed the border while visiting Oman.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mikhail |last=Shilin |url=https://news.liga.net/politics/news/pristayko-ne-otvetil-po-ofitsialnomu-vizitu-zelenskogo-v-oman |url-status=live |trans-title=Prystaiko did not answer about the "official visit" of Zelensky to Oman |title=Пристайко не ответил по "официальному визиту" Зеленского в Оман |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222033017/https://news.liga.net/politics/news/pristayko-ne-otvetil-po-ofitsialnomu-vizitu-zelenskogo-v-oman |archive-date=22 February 2020 |work=Liga.net |date=17 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Vadim |last=Rebrina |url=https://news.liga.net/politics/news/v-op-ne-znayut-s-kem-letal-i-chto-podpisyval-zelenskiy-v-omane |url-status=live |trans-title=In the Presidential Office do not know with whom flew Zelensky and what he signed in Oman |title=В ОП не знают, с кем летал и что подписывал Зеленский в Омане |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222151819/https://news.liga.net/politics/news/v-op-ne-znayut-s-kem-letal-i-chto-podpisyval-zelenskiy-v-omane |archive-date=22 February 2020 |work=Liga.net |date=24 January 2020 }}</ref> On 20 January 2020, Prystaiko followed up by giving a briefing to the press in the Office of the president of Ukraine and saying that he would explain everything about the visit that when the time came.<ref>Mikhail Shilin. ''[https://news.liga.net/politics/news/pristayko-o-vizite-zelenskogo-v-oman-v-svoe-vremya-razyasnim Prystaiko about the visit of Zelensky to Oman: When time comes we will explain (Пристайко о визите Зеленского в Оман: В свое время разъясним)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222033644/https://news.liga.net/politics/news/pristayko-o-vizite-zelenskogo-v-oman-v-svoe-vremya-razyasnim |date=22 February 2020 }}''. Liga.net. 20 January 2020</ref>

=== Foreign relations ===

[[File:Volodymyr Zelenskyy and Ilham Aliyev (2019-12-17) 19.jpg|thumb|Zelenskyy and [[Azerbaijan]]'s president [[Ilham Aliyev]] on 17 December 2019]]
[[File:210831-D-BM568-1144 (51416775670).jpg|thumb|Zelenskyy, Ukraine's defense minister [[Andriy Taran]] and U.S. secretary of defense [[Lloyd Austin]] on 31 August 2021]]
[[File:President Joe Biden and President Volodymyr Zelensky.jpg|thumb|Zelenskyy and U.S. president [[Joe Biden]] on 1 September 2021]]
{{See also|List of international presidential trips made by Volodymyr Zelenskyy}}

Zelenskyy's first official trip abroad as president was to Brussels in June 2019, where he met with [[European Union]] and [[NATO]] officials.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zelensky to meet EU officials on first foreign visit |url=https://www.euronews.com/video/2019/06/04/zelensky-to-meet-eu-officials-on-first-foreign-visit |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604162427/https://www.euronews.com/video/2019/06/04/zelensky-to-meet-eu-officials-on-first-foreign-visit |archive-date=4 June 2019 |access-date=8 June 2019 |website=www.euronews.com}}</ref>

In August 2019, Zelenskyy promised to lift the moratorium on exhuming Polish mass graves in Ukraine after the previous Ukrainian government banned the Polish side from carrying out any exhumations of Polish victims of the [[Ukrainian Insurgent Army]]-perpetrated [[Massacres of Poles in Volhynia and Eastern Galicia|Volhynian massacres]], following the removal of a memorial to the Ukrainian Insurgent Army in [[Hruszowice]], southeastern Poland.<ref>{{Cite news |date=29 August 2019 |title=Ukrainian president to resume exhumation of Poles in Ukraine: report |work=[[Telewizja Polska]] |url=https://polandin.com/44143113/ukrainian-president-to-resume-exhumation-of-poles-in-ukraine-report |url-status=live |access-date=30 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930151936/https://polandin.com/44143113/ukrainian-president-to-resume-exhumation-of-poles-in-ukraine-report |archive-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>

In September 2019, it was reported that U.S. president Donald Trump had allegedly blocked payment of a congressionally mandated $400 million military aid package to Ukraine to pressure Zelenskyy during a July phone call between the two presidents to investigate alleged wrongdoing by Joe Biden and his son [[Hunter Biden]],<ref name="slate" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite news |last1=Vogel |first1=Kenneth P. |last2=Mendel |first2=Iuliia |author-link2=Iuliia Mendel |date=1 May 2019 |title=Biden Faces Conflict of Interest Questions That Are Being Promoted by Trump and Allies |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/01/us/politics/biden-son-ukraine.html |url-status=live |access-date=30 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905135934/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/01/us/politics/biden-son-ukraine.html |archive-date=5 September 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> who took a board seat on Ukrainian natural gas company [[Burisma Holdings]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Schreckinger |first=Ben |date=3 August 2019 |title=The Biden family's strange business history |work=Politico |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/joe-biden-presidential-bid-family-business-history-democrats/ |url-status=live |access-date=30 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113200318/https://www.politico.eu/article/joe-biden-presidential-bid-family-business-history-democrats/ |archive-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> This report was the catalyst for the [[Trump–Ukraine scandal]] and the [[impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]]. Zelenskyy has denied that he was pressured by Trump and declared that "he does not want to interfere in a foreign election."<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Law |first=Tara |date=25 September 2019 |title=Ukrainian President Denies President Trump Pressured Him |url=https://time.com/5686305/zelensky-ukraine-denies-trump-pressure/ |url-status=live |magazine=Time |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117092526/https://time.com/5686305/zelensky-ukraine-denies-trump-pressure/ |archive-date=17 November 2019 |access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>

On a trip to the United States in September 2021, Zelenskyy engaged in talks and commitments with U.S. president Joe Biden,<ref>{{cite web |date=1 September 2021 |title=Biden, Zelensky Discuss Energy, Russia, Ukraine's Future With the West |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-zelensky-to-discuss-energy-russia-ukraines-future-with-the-west-11630497600 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210908101036/https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-zelensky-to-discuss-energy-russia-ukraines-future-with-the-west-11630497600 |archive-date=8 September 2021 |access-date=2 September 2021 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] [[Lloyd Austin]], [[United States Secretary of Energy|Secretary of Energy]] [[Jennifer Granholm]],<ref name="Ukrainian">{{cite web |date=2 September 2021 |title=President Zelensky, First Lady open Ukrainian House in Washington |url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-society/3308681-volodymyr-and-olena-zelensky-open-ukrainian-house-in-washington.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210904074907/https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-society/3308681-volodymyr-and-olena-zelensky-open-ukrainian-house-in-washington.html |archive-date=4 September 2021 |access-date=2 September 2021 |website=[[Ukrinform]]}}</ref> and Secretary of State [[Antony Blinken]].<ref>{{cite web |date=31 August 2021 |title=Zelensky arrives to Washington to meet Blinken, Granholm, Biden |url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/zelensky-arrives-to-washington-to-meet-blinken-granholm-biden.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210831093342/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/zelensky-arrives-to-washington-to-meet-blinken-granholm-biden.html |archive-date=31 August 2021 |access-date=2 September 2021 |website=[[Kyiv Post]]}}</ref> President Zelenskyy and First Lady [[Olena Zelenska]] also took part in the opening of the Ukrainian House in Washington, D.C.<ref name="Ukrainian" /> On the same trip, he met with [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] CEO [[Tim Cook]]<ref>{{cite web |date=2 September 2021 |title=Zelensky to meet with Apple CEO in California on Sept 2, visit Silicon Valley, speak at Stanford University |url=https://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/765621.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210906205320/https://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/765621.html |archive-date=6 September 2021 |access-date=6 September 2021 |website=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] – Ukraine News Agency}}</ref> and with Ukrainians in senior positions at [[Silicon Valley]] tech companies<ref>{{cite news |date=4 September 2021 |title=In California, Zelensky meets with Ukrainians working at Silicon Valley companies |url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-economy/3309992-in-california-zelensky-meets-with-ukrainians-working-at-silicon-valley-companies.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210906222855/https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-economy/3309992-in-california-zelensky-meets-with-ukrainians-working-at-silicon-valley-companies.html |archive-date=6 September 2021 |access-date=6 September 2021 |website=[[Ukrinform]]}}</ref> and spoke at Stanford University.<ref>{{cite web |date=3 September 2021 |title=Zelensky at Stanford: 'Russia's policy is to take, not give' |url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/zelensky-at-stanford-russias-policy-is-to-take-not-give.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210903225549/https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/zelensky-at-stanford-russias-policy-is-to-take-not-give.html |archive-date=3 September 2021 |access-date=6 September 2021 |website=[[Kyiv Post]]}}</ref> While Zelenskyy was still in the U.S., just after delivering a speech at the United Nations, an assassination attempt was made in Ukraine on [[Serhiy Shefir]], his closest aide. Shefir was unhurt in the attack, although his driver was hospitalized with three bullet wounds.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2021/09/22/world/europe/ukraine-assassination-attempt.html Top Adviser to Ukrainian President Is Targeted in an Assassination Attempt] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210923035858/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/09/22/world/europe/ukraine-assassination-attempt.html |date=23 September 2021 }}, ''[[New York Times]]'',  Ivan Nechepurenko and Michael Schwirtz, 22 September 2021. Retrieved 23 September 2021.</ref>

=== 2021–2022 Russo-Ukrainian crisis ===
{{Main|Prelude to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine}}
In April 2021, in response to Russian military build-up at the Ukrainian borders, Zelenskyy spoke to American president Joe Biden and urged NATO members to speed up [[Ukraine–NATO relations|Ukraine's request for membership]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Shylenko |first=Olga |date=8 April 2021 |title=Ukraine's Zelensky on frontline as Merkel urges Putin to pull back troops |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/world/ukraine-s-zelensky-on-frontline-as-merkel-urges-putin-to-pull-back-troops-1.5379725 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210426042440/https://www.ctvnews.ca/world/ukraine-s-zelensky-on-frontline-as-merkel-urges-putin-to-pull-back-troops-1.5379725 |archive-date=26 April 2021 |access-date=16 January 2022 |website=CTVNews}}</ref>
[[File:Working trip to the Donetsk region - 2.jpg|left|thumb|Zelenskyy in the Donetsk region in June 2021]]
On 26 November 2021, Zelenskyy accused Russia and Ukrainian oligarch [[Rinat Akhmetov]] of backing a plan to overthrow his government.<ref>{{Cite news |date=26 November 2021 |title=Zelensky warns Ukraine 'entirely prepared' if Russia attacks |work=France 24 |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20211126-zelensky-warns-ukraine-entirely-prepared-if-russia-attacks |url-status=live |access-date=16 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211216234846/https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20211126-zelensky-warns-ukraine-entirely-prepared-if-russia-attacks |archive-date=16 December 2021}}</ref> Russia denied any involvement in a coup plot and Akhmetov said in a statement that "the information made public by Volodymyr Zelenskiy about attempts to draw me into some kind of coup is an absolute lie. I am outraged by the spread of this lie, no matter what the president's motives are."<ref>{{Cite news |date=26 November 2021 |title=Zelenskiy says Ukraine uncovers coup plot involving Russians; Kremlin denies role |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/ukraine-has-information-about-december-coup-attempt-with-russian-involvement-2021-11-26/ |url-status=live |access-date=16 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211216234438/https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/ukraine-has-information-about-december-coup-attempt-with-russian-involvement-2021-11-26/ |archive-date=16 December 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=27 November 2021 |title=Ukraine's Zelenskiy Says Ready for Russian Escalation, Claims Coup Plot Uncovered |work=[[The Moscow Times]] |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/11/26/ukraines-zelenskiy-says-uncovered-coup-plot-a75679 |url-status=live |access-date=16 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211207000450/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/11/26/ukraines-zelenskiy-says-uncovered-coup-plot-a75679 |archive-date=7 December 2021}}</ref> In December 2021, Zelenskyy called for preemptive action against Russia.<ref>{{Cite news |date=16 December 2021 |title=EU threatens Russia sanctions as NATO backs Ukraine |work=France 24 |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20211216-eu-threatens-russia-sanctions-as-nato-backs-ukraine |url-status=live |access-date=16 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211217010700/https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20211216-eu-threatens-russia-sanctions-as-nato-backs-ukraine |archive-date=17 December 2021}}</ref>

On 19 January 2022, Zelenskyy said in a video message that the country's citizens should not panic and appealed to the media to be "methods of mass information and not mass hysteria."<ref>{{Cite news |date=20 January 2022 |title='Big hype': Zelenskyy urges restraint amid risk of Russian invasion |work=Daily Sabah |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/world/europe/big-hype-zelenskyy-urges-restraint-amid-risk-of-russian-invasion |url-status=live |access-date=28 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220127232825/https://www.dailysabah.com/world/europe/big-hype-zelenskyy-urges-restraint-amid-risk-of-russian-invasion |archive-date=27 January 2022}}</ref><ref name="buzzfeednews-embassy">{{Cite news |date=24 January 2022 |title=Some Ukrainians Are Angry About Washington Ordering Diplomats' Families To Leave The US Embassy |work=BuzzFeed News |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/christopherm51/russia-ukraine-angry-american-departures |url-status=live |access-date=28 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220130172213/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/christopherm51/russia-ukraine-angry-american-departures |archive-date=30 January 2022}}</ref> On 28 January, Zelenskyy called on the West not to create a "panic" in his country over a potential Russian invasion, adding that constant warnings of an "imminent" threat of invasion are putting the [[economy of Ukraine]] at risk.<ref>{{Cite news |date=28 January 2022 |title=Volodymyr Zelensky accuses the West of causing 'panic' with warnings of a Russian invasion that hurts the Ukrainian economy |work=Business Insider |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/ukraine-president-tells-west-to-stop-causing-panic-about-russia-2022-1 |url-status=live |access-date=29 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220129031120/https://www.businessinsider.com/ukraine-president-tells-west-to-stop-causing-panic-about-russia-2022-1 |archive-date=29 January 2022}}</ref> Zelenskyy said that "we do not see a bigger escalation" than in early 2021 when Russia's military build-up started.<ref>{{Cite news |date=28 January 2022 |title=Ukraine to the world: keep calm and stop spreading panic |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/97d15970-3c36-439d-aa38-7402f732efbc |url-status=live |access-date=29 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220129130355/https://www.ft.com/content/97d15970-3c36-439d-aa38-7402f732efbc |archive-date=29 January 2022}}</ref> Zelenskyy and U.S. president Joe Biden disagreed on how imminent the threat was.<ref>{{Cite news |date=28 January 2022 |title=Ukraine crisis: US president Joe Biden tells Zelensky to 'prepare' for Russian invasion |work=The New Zealand Herald |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/ukraine-crisis-us-president-joe-biden-tells-zelensky-to-prepare-for-russian-invasion/2E55YU5QFBU2IW7EPLC5O2O67Y/ |url-status=live |access-date=28 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220128185445/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/ukraine-crisis-us-president-joe-biden-tells-zelensky-to-prepare-for-russian-invasion/2E55YU5QFBU2IW7EPLC5O2O67Y/ |archive-date=28 January 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=28 January 2022 |title=Ukraine's president told Biden to 'calm down' Russian invasion warnings, saying he was creating unwanted panic: report |work=Yahoo News |url=https://news.yahoo.com/ukraines-president-told-biden-calm-104928095.html |url-status=live |access-date=28 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220130111339/https://news.yahoo.com/ukraines-president-told-biden-calm-104928095.html |archive-date=30 January 2022}}</ref>

On 19 February, as worries of a Russian invasion of Ukraine grew, Zelenskyy warned the [[Munich Security Conference]] that Western nations should abandon their "appeasement" attitude toward Moscow. "Ukraine has been granted security assurances in exchange for giving up the world's third-largest nuclear arsenal. We don't have any firearms. And there's no security... But we have a right to urge a transformation from an appeasement policy to one that ensures security and peace," he stated.<ref name=f24msc>{{Cite news |date=19 February 2022 |title=Ukraine is 'longing for peace' says Zelensky at Munich Security Conference |work=France 24 |publisher=France 24 |agency=France 24 |url=https://www.france24.com/en/video/20220219-ukraine-is-longing-for-peace-says-zelensky-at-munich-security-conference |url-status=live |access-date=19 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220219152150/https://www.france24.com/en/video/20220219-ukraine-is-longing-for-peace-says-zelensky-at-munich-security-conference |archive-date=19 February 2022}}</ref>

In the early hours of 24 February, shortly before the start of the Russian invasion, Zelenskyy recorded an address to the citizens of both Ukraine and Russia. He disputed claims of the Russian government about the presence of [[Neo-Nazism#Ukraine|neo-Nazis]] in the Ukrainian government and stated that he had no intention of attacking the Donbas region, while highlighting his personal connections to the area.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cruz Bustillos |first1=Dominic |title=Full Translation: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy's Feb. 23 Speech |url=https://www.lawfareblog.com/full-translation-ukrainian-president-volodymyr-zelenskyys-feb-23-speech |website=Lawfare |access-date=25 February 2022 |language=en |date=24 February 2022 |archive-date=25 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220225024314/https://www.lawfareblog.com/full-translation-ukrainian-president-volodymyr-zelenskyys-feb-23-speech |url-status=live }}</ref> In part of the address, he spoke in Russian to the people of Russia, appealing to them to pressure their leadership to prevent war:
{{Quotation|Who will suffer the most from this? People. Who does not want this more than anyone? People. Who can prevent this? People.

Are these people present among you? I am sure there are. Public figures, journalists, musicians, actors, athletes, scientists, doctors, bloggers, stand-up comedians, Tik-Tokers and many more. Regular people. Regular, normal people. Men, women, the elderly, children, fathers, and most importantly, mothers. Just like people in Ukraine. Just like the authorities in Ukraine, no matter how much they try to convince you otherwise.

I know that they will not show this appeal of mine on Russian television. But the citizens of Russia must see it. They must know the truth. And the truth is that this needs to stop, before it is too late. And if the Russian leadership does not want to sit down at the table with us for the sake of peace, then perhaps, they will sit down at the table with you.

[[Do the Russians Want War?|Do Russians want war?]] I would very much like to answer this question. But the answer depends only on you, the citizens of the Russian Federation.}}

The speech was widely described as "emotional" and "astonishing".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/649982cc-d054-4c73-94be-e907584fe69a|title=Volodymyr Zelensky's appeal to Russians: 'The people of Ukraine want peace'|first=Polina|last=Ivanova|newspaper=Financial Times|date=24 February 2022|access-date=19 March 2022|archive-date=19 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220319142646/https://www.ft.com/content/649982cc-d054-4c73-94be-e907584fe69a|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/newsletter/london-playbook/breaking-putin-bombs-kyiv-declares-war-blasts-rock-major-cities/|title=London Playbook: BREAKING: Putin declares war — Bombs Kyiv — Blasts rock major cities|date=24 February 2022|website=POLITICO|access-date=19 March 2022|archive-date=24 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220324024154/https://www.politico.eu/newsletter/london-playbook/breaking-putin-bombs-kyiv-declares-war-blasts-rock-major-cities/|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine ===
{{Main|2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine}}
[[File:Заявка України на членство у Європейському Союзі, 1.jpg|thumb|[[Verkhovna Rada]] chairman [[Ruslan Stefanchuk]], Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy and Ukrainian Prime Minister [[Denys Shmyhal]] after signing of the application for membership in the European Union during the war on 28 February 2022]]
[[File:Volodymyr Zelenskyy paid a visit to the wounded defenders of Ukraine undergoing treatment at a military hospital (51937554922).jpg|thumb|President Volodymyr Zelenskyy visiting a military hospital for soldiers fighting in the [[Kyiv offensive (2022)|Kyiv Oblast]], 13 March]]
====First phase: Invasion of Ukraine (24 February – 7 April)====
On the morning of 24 February, Putin [[On conducting a special military operation|announced]] that Russia was initiating a "special military operation" in the Donbas. Russian missiles struck a number of military targets in Ukraine, and Zelenskyy declared martial law.<ref>{{Cite news|date=24 February 2022|title=Ukraine conflict: Russian forces attack from three sides|language=en-GB|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-60503037|access-date=24 February 2022|archive-date=24 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220224204817/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-60503037|url-status=live}}</ref> Zelenskyy also announced that [[Russia–Ukraine relations|diplomatic relations with Russia]] were being severed, effective immediately.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.interfax.ru/world/824153 |title=Украина разорвала дипломатические отношения с Россией |website=[[Interfax]] |date=24 February 2022 |access-date=24 February 2022 |archive-date=24 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220224095330/https://www.interfax.ru/world/824153 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later in the day, he announced general mobilisation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ukrainian president signs decree on general mobilisation of population -Interfax |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/ukrainian-president-signs-decree-general-mobilisation-population-interfax-2022-02-24/ |access-date=25 February 2022 |work=Reuters |date=24 February 2022 |language=en |archive-date=25 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220225025205/https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/ukrainian-president-signs-decree-general-mobilisation-population-interfax-2022-02-24/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 25 February, Zelenskyy said that despite Russia's claim that it was targeting only military sites, civilian sites were also being hit.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ukraine president orders full military mobilisation |url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/national/19950945.ukraine-president-orders-full-military-mobilisation/ |access-date=25 February 2022 |work=The National |agency=PA |date=24 February 2022 |language=en |archive-date=26 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220226073516/https://www.thenational.scot/news/national/19950945.ukraine-president-orders-full-military-mobilisation/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In an early morning address that day, Zelenskyy said that his intelligence services had identified him as Russia's top target, but that he is staying in Kyiv and his family will remain in the country. "They want to destroy Ukraine politically by destroying the head of state", he said.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Daryna|last1=Krasnolutska|first2=Alan|last2=Crawford|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/putin-unbowed-as-russia-presses-ahead-with-invasion-toward-kyiv-1.1728642|title=Putin Unbowed as Russia Presses Ahead With Invasion Toward Kyiv|work=BNN Bloomberg|date=25 February 2022|access-date=25 February 2022|archive-date=26 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220226073516/https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/putin-unbowed-as-russia-presses-ahead-with-invasion-toward-kyiv-1.1728642|url-status=live}}</ref> In the early hours of 26 February, during the most significant assault by Russian troops on the capital of Kyiv, the United States government and Turkish president [[Recep Tayyip Erdoğan]] urged Zelenskyy to evacuate to a safer location, and both offered assistance for such an effort. Zelenskyy turned down both offers and opted to remain in Kyiv with its defense forces, saying that "the fight is here [in Kyiv]; I need ammunition, not a ride".<ref>{{Cite news |first1=Shane |last1=Harris |first2=Ellen |last2=Francis |first3=Robyn |last3=Dixon |date=25 February 2022 |title=U.S. stands ready to evacuate Zelensky, Russia's 'No. 1 target' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2022/02/25/russia-ukraine-president-zelensky-family-target/ |url-status=live |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=26 February 2022 |archive-date=25 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220225230325/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2022/02/25/russia-ukraine-president-zelensky-family-target/ }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first1=Yuras |last1=Karmanau |first2=Jim |last2=Heintz |first3=Vladimir |last3=Isachenkov |first4=Dasha |last4=Litvinova |date=25 February 2022 |title=Ukraine's capital under threat as Russia presses invasion |url=https://apnews.com/article/russia-ukraine-vladimir-putin-volodymyr-zelenskyy-boris-johnson-business-08f569df695831ee467979527ea2e241 |url-status=live |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=26 February 2022 |archive-date=25 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220225142052/https://apnews.com/article/russia-ukraine-vladimir-putin-volodymyr-zelenskyy-boris-johnson-business-08f569df695831ee467979527ea2e241 }}</ref><ref name=":5" />

More than 90% of Ukrainians supported the actions of Zelenskyy,<ref>{{cite news |title=93 Percent of Ukrainians Believe Russia Will Be Defeated: Poll |url=https://www.newsweek.com/93-percent-ukrainians-believe-russia-will-defeated-poll-1689796 |work=Newsweek |date=20 March 2022 |access-date=3 April 2022 |archive-date=2 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220402025937/https://www.newsweek.com/93-percent-ukrainians-believe-russia-will-defeated-poll-1689796 |url-status=live }}</ref> including more than 90% in western and central Ukraine and more than 80% in Russian-speaking regions in eastern and southern Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Majority of Ukrainians believe they will win against Russia - poll |url=https://www.jpost.com/international/article-698853 |work=The Jerusalem Post |date=28 February 2022 |access-date=3 April 2022 |archive-date=3 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220403075546/https://www.jpost.com/international/article-698853 |url-status=live }}</ref> A [[Pew Research Center]] poll found that 72% of Americans had confidence in Zelenskyy's handling of international affairs.<ref>{{cite news |title=Americans have more confidence in Zelenskyy than Biden when it comes to world affairs |url=https://www.npr.org/2022/03/31/1089958981/zelenskyy-approval-rating-us?t=1648991304507 |work=NPR |date=31 March 2022 |access-date=3 April 2022 |archive-date=4 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220404015143/https://www.npr.org/2022/03/31/1089958981/zelenskyy-approval-rating-us?t=1648991304507 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Zelenskyy has gained worldwide recognition as the wartime leader of Ukraine during the Russian invasion; historian [[Andrew Roberts (historian)|Andrew Roberts]] compared him to [[Winston Churchill]].<ref name=deutsche-welle>{{cite news |title=Ukraine's Volodymyr Zelenskyy: From comedian to national hero |url=https://www.dw.com/en/ukraines-volodymyr-zelenskyy-from-comedian-to-national-hero/a-60924507 |access-date=27 February 2022 |work=[[Deutsche Welle]] |archive-date=28 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220228070324/https://www.dw.com/en/ukraines-volodymyr-zelenskyy-from-comedian-to-national-hero/a-60924507 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>Other sources:
*{{cite news |title=3 years ago Zelenskyy was a TV comedian. Now he's standing up to Putin's army. |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/zelenskyy-ukraine-russia-putin-invasion-rcna17661 |access-date=27 February 2022 |work=NBC News |archive-date=1 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220301044134/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/zelenskyy-ukraine-russia-putin-invasion-rcna17661 |url-status=live }}
*{{cite news |title=Actor-turned-president Zelensky grows on stage as Ukraine's war-time leader |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/actor-turned-president-zelensky-grows-on-stage-as-ukraines-war-time-leader/ |access-date=27 February 2022 |work=Times of Israel |quote=he is now the face of national defiance, winning rave reviews as a war-time leader |archive-date=27 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220227185114/https://www.timesofisrael.com/actor-turned-president-zelensky-grows-on-stage-as-ukraines-war-time-leader/ |url-status=live }}
*{{cite news |title=Zelenskyy's unlikely journey, from comedy to wartime leader |url=https://apnews.com/article/russia-ukraine-volodymyr-zelenskyy-kyiv-poland-europe-c270027c825e009ed66988bb98a3476e |access-date=27 February 2022 |work=AP News |archive-date=28 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220228173754/https://apnews.com/article/russia-ukraine-volodymyr-zelenskyy-kyiv-poland-europe-c270027c825e009ed66988bb98a3476e |url-status=live }}
